text: I almost passed on the last one and I'm pretty sure I'll pass on this one. To think that Trump, who I personally do not cheer for, or any politician or Christian on either side of the aisle would condone or sanction the Purge is ridiculous. For a dystopian novel or film to be effective, there must be tie-ins to the real world which may or may not be turned completely on their head by the author or screenwriter. I understand this as well as anyone else. However, this is more than achieved by the excessive flag-waving, the largely skewed view of the American way which comes with the flag-waving, and the propaganda. Thus, there is no need to attack a certain political candidate. Doing so comes across as extremely tacky.

text: It's amazing to see how far this series has come since its first entry in 2013. I remember first hearing about the concept and it terrifying me. All of the hype building up to the first film made me very excited, but after seeing the film opening weekend, I was massively let down. Instead of exploring the horrific events that occur in the streets (innocent people being targeted and murdered, revenge stories, etc) the filmmakers chose to put a weird twist on the home invasion genre, seemingly with the purge occurring in the background as a plot device, rather than the purge being the actual PLOT itself. Then, the sequel was announced and my worries were somewhat put to rest as rumor began to spread that the film would explore the effects of the purge in the streets and on normal people. The second film was a well made thriller in my opinion, and was a lot of what I expected out of the first film. Now, with the third entry soon to be released, I'm pleasantly surprised to see the political direction they're choosing to take the series. What started out as a low-budget, high concept film that had grandiose undertones which were never fully explored, has now turned into a series that I can actually say I like and I'm looking forward to. It's interesting to be looking at this series this way, too, because Ouija (another Blumhouse series) seems to be taking the same route. Whereas the first Ouija film was a critical failure but did well at the box-office, Jason Blum seems to actually be paying attention to the QUALITY of his films on top of the money. I say this because he hired Mike Flanagan (Oculus, Hush) to write and direct the Ouija sequel, and Jason has openly said in interviews that he felt the first Ouija film didn't quite hit the mark, but that he believes the sequel will leave people pleasantly surprised. Jason Blum doesn't get the credit he deserves. Sure, it may seem like he's only in the business for the money with his low-budget model and such. But I believe he truly cares about the horror genre as well. Why else would he be listening to the critics and trying to improve on his franchises? Keep up the good work, Blumhouse!

text: Humanity? What's humanity? This is why Donald Trump shouldn't surprise people. Perhaps there is no such thing as humanity. Perhaps deep down we ARE a species of animalistic savages which can never learn to love each other as brothers and sisters, regardless of physical, mental, cultural, and political differences. Perhaps we should have gone gently into that good night a long time ago. But I refuse to believe that. I refuse to believe that this blood and death could ever hold humanity forever. There is no question that it has before, such as in World War II. But so long as a mother or father looks at their child and knows instinctively that they want nothing but the best life for him or her, as he or she has given them the greatest gift life can offer - life itself - I know that there is still goodness in this world, and that someday that love of and for life will be extended into a love of the lives of ALL others. You might say I'm a dreamer, but I'm not the only one.

In the best way. The social satire looks great, the violence and atmosphere are positively disturbing... I don't know if these movies are going to be nearly as interesting if we see a substantial change in America's political climate, but for the moment, this is fucking great.  I do hope we see this story come to an end, like we see this senator elected and this is the end of The Purge. Because the thing is, we can keep having these movies and keep the stakes high, as long as they keep changing protagonists, we won't know who will survive if we go back to an earlier Purge night. I just want this one, since it's supposed to be about the end, to be about the end.

text: I sometimes wish the Purge movies would explore different aspects of crime than just murder. Not EVERYONE would go out and kill someone, there are people who would see the purge as a opportunity to steal things like the newest ps4 or xbox, movies, food, money etc.  Yes, murderous psychopaths as shown in these films exist and there would definitely be murders on Purge night but it seems like that's the only aspect of crime that's out there in these films and the longer this series goes on, it will eventually run out of steam and become boring. There are other thongs people would do on a free night like this. Steal, murder, deal illegal drugs publicly.. other things or just stay at home.. It would be interesting if a purge film had three story arcs on three different sets of people doing different things on Purge night. One story arc would follow a group of (likable) psychopaths going on a murder spree (murder aspect), another story arc have a group of people or teenagers having fun going around the city stealing things (robbery aspect) and another have a family just trying to survive the night at home when a group of angry druggies try to break in and kill them because the husband who secretly has a drug problem has been secretly buying drugs from them and still owes their money. (illegal drugs aspect)  I don't know something different, rather than the same things happening every film: Showing characters who need to survive a world of raving maniacs killing people left and right for no reason. This would bring a breath of fresh air to the franchise if it ever were to continue. But looks like its trying to be the last.. but that's the thing about Hollywood, you never know which one is truly the last film in a successful franchise.

text: Sooo, this might just be me and my crazy feminist ideas, but am I the only one who sees the connection between the most recent Purge movie (The Purge: Election Year) and the modern feminist movement that we're living in? This movie has been advertised for like two(?) years now and I just think it's weird how in this most recent era of woman politicians and feminists saying "hey, don't rape people" among other things like more woman main characters in blockbuster dude dominated roles and women having a louder voice than ever, this slasher movie comes out where the entire plot is centered around a counsel of dudes who's goal it is to murder the woman politician who's main platform is "hey, don't kill people"....  It reminds me of what was happening in 70s slasher films with the spawn of the "final girl" trope and the pattern of brutally murdering half naked women in the middle of another big feminist movement. It just feels like history is repeating it's self here you know? Because as much as people will say "it's just a movie" movies, especially horror/slasher movies are a reflection of the time they're made. And right now we're living in a time of a modern feminist movement and also an antifeminist movement in the most recognizable form of "men's rights activism" (who's leader literally wants rape to be legalized and was going to hold rallies for it: http://www.washingtontimes.com/â€¦/roosh-v-pro-rape-activistâ€¦/ ) I don't know dude, you overanalyze things when film study is one of your hobbies...

text: My review: WARNING SPOILERS  This is what is happening right now. Not in a literal sense of course.  There is a shadowy group of people (super rich,  most likely involved in politics or have a huge influence bc of their money) following a cult leader who has convinced them that the only way to become pure is to kill off everyone who disagrees with them or is not part of their cult.  This movie was filled with subliminal messages to desensitize people from what is really going on. During the movie there was so much racial propaganda...  Blacks vs white. Also the chick who tried to steal the candy; she later came back and was blasting Miley Cyrus. Shows how fucked the younger generation is being brought up. They listen to trap music and music that does nothing but influence them to become disrespectful. I could go on.   The last interesting point is how they made it a female running for president to "save"  the country. I read through many comment and see a bunch of bullshit. "If trump wins this will happen" many of these comments are from younger kids I presume, trying to be funny. Still it goes to show how uneducated they are about the issues and only know what the TV has told them.   I did enjoy the movie though. It's very interesting seeing what kind of subliminal messages Hollywood is trying to push to your ideals.   Let me know what you guys thought of the movie!
